    "definition": "A tube-shaped invagination of the epidermis that extends through the dermis into the subcutaneous layer. The follicle is the complete structural and functional unit that anchors each hair and drives its cyclic production. Each person has approximately 100,000 follicles on the scalp \u2014 fixed at birth, never gained.",
    "function": "Produces the hair shaft through continuous cyclic activity across anagen, catagen, telogen, and exogen phases. Regulates all phase transitions in response to hormonal, nutritional, inflammatory, and neurogenic signals. Maintains immune privilege in its lower segment. Hosts bulge stem cells responsible for regeneration after each cycle and after injury.",
    "cycle_phases": {
      "anagen": {
        "name": "Growth Phase",
        "duration_scalp": "2 to 7 years \u2014 determined by genetics, nutrition, and hormonal environment",
        "percentage_healthy_scalp": "85 to 90 percent",
        "activity": "Matrix cells in the lower follicle divide continuously. Hair shaft produced at 0.35 to 0.44 mm per day.",
        "rate_limiting_biology": "Oxygen delivery via dermal papilla capillaries is the primary rate limiter. Iron deficiency reduces haemoglobin oxygen-carrying capacity \u2192 matrix hypoxia \u2192 anagen shortening.",
        "anagen_length_determinants": "Androgen sensitivity of dermal papilla AR. Wnt signal strength from dermal papilla. IGF-1 availability. Nutritional substrate availability for matrix. Thyroid hormone T3 level at nuclear receptor in matrix cells."
      },
      "catagen": {
        "name": "Controlled Regression Phase",
        "duration": "2 to 3 weeks",
        "percentage_healthy_scalp": "1 to 2 percent",
        "activity": "Dermal papilla secretes TGF-beta-2 and activin A signalling controlled apoptosis of the lower follicle. Matrix cells cease dividing. Club hair forms. Dermal papilla condenses and retracts upward.",
        "premature_trigger": "DHT upregulates TGF-beta-2 in dermal papilla \u2014 shortening anagen and triggering premature catagen. Cortisol locally upregulates follicular CRH \u2014 same outcome. Nutritional deficiency triggers catagen by ATP and substrate depletion."
      },
      "telogen": {
        "name": "Rest and Club Hair Anchoring Phase",
        "duration": "3 to 4 months",
        "percentage_healthy_scalp": "10 to 15 percent",
        "activity": "Follicle inactive. Club hair anchored by trichilemmal keratins. BMP signalling from dermal papilla keeps bulge stem cells quiescent.",
        "shedding_rate": "50 to 100 telogen hairs shed per day is normal",
        "telogen_effluvium_trigger": "Systemic physiological shock (illness, nutritional crash, surgery, delivery, extreme stress) \u2192 sudden mass synchronised entry of follicles into telogen \u2192 2 to 3 month lag \u2192 dramatic shedding episode. Iron deficiency is the most common nutritional trigger."
      },
      "exogen": {
        "name": "Active Hair Shaft Release Phase",
        "duration": "2 to 5 days",
        "activity": "Enzyme-driven active release of club hair from the follicle. LEKTI protease inhibitor and serine proteases regulate this separately from telogen timing.",
        "significance": "Exogen failure can cause two hairs to co-occupy one follicle temporarily \u2014 pili gemini \u2014 which is benign."
      },
      "kenogen": {
        "name": "Empty Follicle Phase",
        "note": "A phase sometimes recognised between exogen and next anagen where follicle is empty. Prolonged kenogen reduces visible density even before significant miniaturisation."
      }
    },
    "cellular_mechanism": "Matrix cells divide at one of the highest mitotic rates in the human body \u2014 comparable only to intestinal epithelium and bone marrow. This mitotic rate demands exceptional local oxygen concentration, continuous amino acid availability, zinc for transcription factor activity, and B12 plus folate for DNA methylation and nucleotide synthesis. Bulge stem cells in the outer root sheath express keratin 15 and CD34 markers. At the onset of each anagen cycle, dermal papilla signals (primarily Wnt) overcome BMP inhibition and activate these quiescent stem cells to proliferate and re-populate the lower follicle.",
    "molecular_mechanism": {
      "anagen_initiation": "Dermal papilla Wnt3a/Wnt10b \u2192 beta-catenin stabilisation in bulge stem cells \u2192 TCF/LEF transcription \u2192 stem cell activation and lower follicle reconstruction. IGF-1 via PI3K/Akt promotes cell survival during this reconstruction. Vitamin D receptor (VDR) activation in bulge is required to overcome BMP4/7 quiescence signalling \u2014 the mechanistic basis of Vitamin D deficiency hair loss.",
      "anagen_maintenance": "VEGF from dermal papilla drives angiogenesis maintaining capillary network. FGF-7 (KGF) and FGF-10 from dermal papilla sustain matrix keratinocyte proliferation. Wnt signal strength correlates with anagen duration \u2014 stronger Wnt \u2192 longer anagen.",
      "catagen_trigger": "TGF-beta-2, activin A, and FGF-5 from dermal papilla signal apoptosis. Cortisol upregulates local CRH production within the follicle \u2014 CRH acts directly on follicle receptors to accelerate catagen. DHT upregulates TGF-beta-2. Nutritional stress reduces IGF-1 \u2014 removing the anti-apoptotic survival signal for matrix cells.",
      "telogen_maintenance": "BMP2 and BMP4 secreted by dermal papilla during telogen bind BMPR1a on bulge stem cells \u2192 SMAD1/5/8 signalling \u2192 inhibition of Wnt target gene transcription \u2192 stem cells remain quiescent.",
      "VDR_anagen_gate": "Vitamin D receptor in bulge acts as a molecular gatekeeper \u2014 VDR activation reduces BMP inhibitory signalling allowing Wnt to initiate anagen. VDR knockout mice show arrested hair cycling \u2014 confirming this gate function.",
      "miniaturisation_cascade": "DHT binds AR in dermal papilla \u2192 upregulates TGF-beta-2 and DKK-1 (Wnt antagonist) \u2192 paracrine inhibition of matrix cell proliferation \u2192 shorter anagen each cycle \u2192 smaller follicle volume each cycle \u2192 thinner hair shaft each cycle \u2192 eventually follicle produces only vellus hair \u2192 clinically visible as hair thinning and recession."
    },
    "telogen_effluvium_physiology": {
      "mechanism": "A physiological shock event \u2192 acute reduction in systemic IGF-1 and growth signals \u2192 mass synchronised transition of anagen follicles to telogen \u2192 2 to 3 month lag (telogen duration) \u2192 all follicles simultaneously reach exogen \u2192 dramatic episodic shedding",
      "common_triggers_by_ref": [
        "NUT_IRON_001",
