    "structure": "Dermal Papilla",
    "parent_system": "SYS_HAIR_001",
    "parent_structure": "BIO_FOLLICLE_001",
    "definition": "A compact cluster of 150 to 300 specialised mesenchymal fibroblast-like cells at the base of the hair follicle, encased within the hair bulb, forming the primary signalling command centre. The dermal papilla is the brain of the hair follicle \u2014 every instruction to grow, maintain, regress, or miniaturise originates here.",
    "function": "Secretes paracrine growth factors and inhibitory signals to matrix cells and bulge stem cells, controlling cycle phase, hair shaft diameter, and anagen duration. Expresses androgen receptors \u2014 the site where DHT executes androgenetic alopecia. Directs vascular supply to the matrix via VEGF-driven angiogenesis. Maintains inductive capacity \u2014 can regenerate a complete new follicle when transplanted.",
    "cellular_mechanism": "Dermal papilla cells are unlike any other fibroblast population \u2014 they retain embryonic inductive properties throughout life. They survive catagen within a condensed cluster and guide the bulge stem cells to reconstruct the lower follicle at the start of each new anagen. Their number correlates with hair shaft diameter \u2014 larger papilla \u2192 thicker hair shaft. In androgenetic alopecia, progressive papilla volume reduction produces progressively thinner shafts.",
