    ],
    "definition": "The connective tissue layer between the epidermis and subcutaneous fat \u2014 1 to 4 mm thick, comprising 90 percent of skin thickness. Houses the structural protein matrix (collagen, elastin), the vascular supply network for skin, sensory nerve endings, hair follicle roots, sebaceous glands, eccrine sweat glands, and the fibroblasts that produce and maintain the extracellular matrix.",
    "function": "Provides tensile strength and elasticity via collagen and elastin networks. Supplies the avascular epidermis with all nutrients via capillary diffusion. Senses temperature, pressure, pain, and touch via specialised receptors. Generates the structural scaffold within which hair follicles operate. Regulates skin hydration through glycosaminoglycan water retention.",
    "layers": {
      "papillary_dermis": "Loose connective tissue immediately below epidermis. Contains fine collagen type III fibrils, rich capillary loops (papillary loops) that nourish epidermis, and free nerve endings. Site of immediate immune responses.",
      "reticular_dermis": "Deeper, denser layer with thick interwoven type I collagen bundles, elastin fibres, and fewer cells. Provides the primary mechanical strength of skin."
    },
    "cellular_mechanism": "Fibroblasts are the dominant cell type \u2014 they produce and continuously remodel collagen, elastin, fibronectin, and glycosaminoglycans. Fibroblast activity is regulated by mechanical tension (low tension \u2192 reduced collagen synthesis \u2014 explaining skin laxity after weight loss), growth factors (TGF-beta-1 stimulates collagen), and hormones (estrogen maintains fibroblast activity; cortisol suppresses it). Mast cells in the dermis mediate allergic and inflammatory responses. Dendritic cells participate in immune surveillance.",
    "molecular_mechanism": {
      "collagen_remodelling": "Collagen synthesis by fibroblasts is balanced against degradation by matrix metalloproteinases (MMP-1, MMP-3, MMP-9). UV radiation activates AP-1 transcription factor \u2192 MMP-1 upregulation \u2192 collagen degradation. Cortisol reduces TGF-beta-1-driven collagen synthesis AND increases MMP expression \u2192 net collagen loss. For full collagen synthesis pathway see BIO_COLLAGEN_001.",
      "elastin_network": {
        "structure": "Elastin fibres are crosslinked polymers of tropoelastin monomers by lysyl oxidase (copper-dependent enzyme)",
        "function": "Provides rapid elastic recoil \u2014 skin returns to shape after deformation. Elastin molecules can stretch to 150 percent of resting length.",
        "degradation": "Elastin is not regenerated efficiently after age 30. UV-induced elastases (MMP-12) degrade elastin \u2192 solar elastosis \u2014 permanently damaged elastin seen as leathery, furrowed skin in sun-damaged areas",
        "copper_dependency": "Lysyl oxidase requires copper for crosslinking both elastin and collagen. Copper deficiency \u2192 uncrosslinked, fragile fibres. Ref: NUT_COPPER_001"
      },
      "glycosaminoglycan_water_retention": {
        "hyaluronic_acid": "The major GAG of dermis. 1g HA holds up to 6 litres water. Produced by fibroblasts via HAS (hyaluronan synthase) enzymes.",
        "HA_degradation": "Hyaluronidase enzymes and ROS degrade HA. UV exposure \u2192 ROS \u2192 HA degradation \u2192 reduced dermal hydration \u2192 wrinkle formation",
        "estrogen_regulation": "Estrogen upregulates HAS gene expression and reduces hyaluronidase activity. Estrogen decline at menopause \u2192 rapid HA reduction \u2192 dry, thin skin. Ref: HOR_ESTROGEN_001"
      },
      "AGE_formation": {
        "process": "Blood glucose non-enzymatically attaches to collagen lysine and arginine residues \u2192 Maillard reaction \u2192 Schiff base \u2192 Amadori products \u2192 advanced glycation end products (AGEs)",
        "consequences": "AGEs form irreversible crosslinks between collagen fibres \u2192 rigid, yellow, mechanically compromised matrix. AGE-RAGE receptor binding \u2192 NF-kB \u2192 inflammatory cytokines \u2192 further matrix degradation \u2192 accelerated skin ageing",
        "insulin_resistance_link": "BLD_INSULIN_RESISTANCE_001 maintains chronically elevated glucose \u2192 faster AGE accumulation. Even postprandial glucose spikes contribute cumulatively over years."
      }
    },
